				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I draw my levels using GIMP, and then I feed the level's image, along with an image of the tileset used, to a script I coded that translates the levels into a big 2D array of tiles/blocks, and then feeds that to another script that encodes the data into the format that my game engine expects.<br /><br />I also have scripts to do the opposite job, which's converting the binary data to a full level image using a tileset image, so I can edit levels for which I don't own the source images anymore, or so I can change tilesets without having to redraw entire maps.<br /><br />Most sane people would use one of the generic map editors out there, and convert their output to the final binary format, but I prefer the freedom of a graphics editor, which have configurable grids, layers, easy copy &amp; paste, and so on.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

